But it returns me the empty list.

answer:
The issue with your JSON file is that you have duplicate keys ("name"), which isn't valid JSON. Each key in a JSON object must be unique. Instead, you should use an array of names. Here's a complete solution that reads names from a properly formatted JSON file:

```java
import org.json.simple.JSONArray;
import org.json.simple.JSONObject;
import org.json.simple.parser.JSONParser;
import java.io.FileReader;
import java.util.ArrayList;
import java.util.List;

public class NameReader {
    private List<String> datasource = new ArrayList<>();

    public List<String> getNames() {
        JSONParser parser = new JSONParser();
        try {
            // Read JSON file (use correct path to your file)
            Object obj = parser.parse(new FileReader("names.json"));

            // If your JSON is an array of objects with "name" property
            if (obj instanceof JSONArray) {
                JSONArray namesArray = (JSONArray) obj;
                for (Object item : namesArray) {
                    JSONObject nameObj = (JSONObject) item;
                    String name = (String) nameObj.get("name");
                    datasource.add(name);
                }
            } 
            // If your JSON is a simple array of strings
            else if (obj instanceof JSONObject) {
                JSONObject jsonObject = (JSONObject) obj;
                // This handles the case where names are values of unique keys
                for (Object value : jsonObject.values()) {
                    datasource.add((String) value);
                }
            }
        } catch (Exception e) {
            e.printStackTrace();
        }
        return datasource;
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        NameReader reader = new NameReader();
        List<String> names = reader.getNames();
        System.out.println("Names found: " + names);
    }
}
```

For this to work, your JSON file should be in one of these formats:

1. Array of objects:
```json
[
    {"name": "Luis Lopez"},
    {"name": "Armando Guascogne Ursular"},
    {"name": "Brancar Diego"}
]
```

2. Simple array:
```json
["Luis Lopez", "Armando Guascogne Ursular", "Brancar Diego"]
```

3. Object with unique keys (though this isn't ideal for your use case):
```json
{
    "name1": "Luis Lopez",
    "name2": "Armando Guascogne Ursular",
    "name3": "Brancar Diego"
}
```

Make sure to:
1. Have the correct path to your JSON file
2. Add the json-simple library to your project (if using Maven, add the dependency)
3. Use one of the valid JSON formats shown above

