Here's a complete Java subroutine that computes the standard deviation of an array of floating-point values:

```java
public class StandardDeviationCalculator {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        float[] data = {3.3f, 5.6f, 7.8f, 5.4f, 9.9f};
        float stdDev = calculateStandardDeviation(data);
        System.out.printf("Standard Deviation: %.4f%n", stdDev);
    }

    /**
     * Calculates the standard deviation of an array of floating-point values
     * @param data array of floating-point values
     * @return the standard deviation of the input values
     */
    public static float calculateStandardDeviation(float[] data) {
        if (data == null || data.length == 0) {
            throw new IllegalArgumentException("Input array cannot be null or empty");
        }

        // Calculate mean (average)
        float sum = 0.0f;
        for (float num : data) {
            sum += num;
        }
        float mean = sum / data.length;

        // Calculate sum of squared differences from mean
        float squaredDiffSum = 0.0f;
        for (float num : data) {
            squaredDiffSum += Math.pow(num - mean, 2);
        }

        // Calculate variance and standard deviation
        float variance = squaredDiffSum / data.length;
        float standardDeviation = (float) Math.sqrt(variance);

        return standardDeviation;
    }
}
```

